          {/* ========== §9 FORWARD VIEW ========== */}
          <section className="section">
            <div className="section__num">9</div>
            <span className="section__kicker">Forward View</span>
            <h2>Outlook — April 2026: Where We Stand</h2>

            <p>
              As of 19 April 2026, the Indian market is navigating three
              simultaneous streams of geopolitical risk: renewed US-India trade
              friction following the 2025 tariff episode, the tail of the
              2024–25 Middle East flare-ups, and a still-elevated India-Pakistan
              posture post Operation Sindoor. None individually qualifies as a
              Tier-3 event. Collectively, they are pushing Nifty valuations to a
              mid-cycle pause, not a cycle break.
            </p>

            <h3>What we are watching, in priority order</h3>
            <div className="watchlist">
              <div className="watch-item">
                <strong>Brent crude above $95.</strong>
                <p>
                  The single highest-impact transmission channel for Tier-2
                  events into Indian equity markets. Every sustained move above
                  $90 in our sample has coincided with a &gt;5% Nifty drawdown.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div className="watch-item">
                <strong>US 10-year yield and DXY.</strong>
                <p>
                  FII flows follow the dollar. A DXY move above 106 or US 10Y
                  above 4.75% historically coincides with heavy FII selling in
                  Indian small and midcaps — our hunting ground.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div className="watch-item">
                <strong>FII monthly flow prints.</strong>
                <p>
                  Track at the weekly level. A reversal from consistent selling
                  to buying has led every major Tier-1 and Tier-2 rebound in our
                  sample by 3–5 weeks.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div className="watch-item">
                <strong>Domestic SIP inflows.</strong>
                <p>
                  The structural floor. Monthly SIP flows above ₹25,000 crore
                  materially cushion every subsequent drawdown. Watch for any
                  slowdown as a leading indicator of depth.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div className="watch-item">
                <strong>Tier-1 surprise event risk.</strong>
                <p>
                  Residual probability of a fresh cross-border flare-up. Our
                  base rate says the market will recover within weeks — but
                  tactical liquidity needs to be ready at all times.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <p>
              <strong>Bottom line.</strong> Every significant bull market in
              Indian history has been built on the foundation of a fear-driven
              dislocation — Kargil in 1999, post-26/11 in 2009,
              post-demonetisation in 2017, post-COVID from 2020–24. The common
              thread is not the absence of fear; it is the willingness of
              patient, disciplined capital to deploy <em>into</em> the fear. The
              backtest is settled. The next event is not a question of{" "}
              <em>if</em> — only
              <em>when</em>.
            </p>

            <div className="closing">
              <blockquote>
                Wars end. Panic fades. Markets recover. The base rate is
                overwhelmingly in favour of patient, quality-anchored capital —
                and over the last 26 years, it has only gotten stronger.
              </blockquote>
              <div className="closing__sig">
                — <strong>Rahul Das</strong> &amp; <strong>Rakesh Das</strong> ·
                LNPR Capital Research · 19 April 2026
              </div>
            </div>
          </section>

